{"title_page": "Jack Renton", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = John (Jack) Renton\n| image              = \n| birth_date         = Unknown, presumably around 1840\n| birth_place        = [[Orkney]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| death_date         = 1878\n| death_place        = [[Aoba Island]], [[Vanuatu]]\n| occupation         = Seaman, slave, [[headhunting|headhunter]]\n}}\n'''John (Jack) Renton''', also known as \"The White Headhunter\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Randell |first1=Nigel |title=The White Headhunter: The Story of a 19th-Century Sailor Who Survived a South Seas Heart of Darkness |date=July 17, 2003 |publisher=Carroll & Graf |isbn=0786712562}}</ref>, was a Scottish seaman from [[Orkney]] who was shipwrecked in 1868 and landed at Maana'oba Island in the [[Solomon Islands]]. He became a slave of a bigman named Kabbou for 8 years, in which he learnt the Lau language, participated in the island's culture, and became a [[headhunting|headhunter]]. He is the only European to have been a headhunter and was the first European to live for a long period on [[Malaita]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Biographical entry: Renton, John |url=http://www.solomonencyclopaedia.net/biogs/E000656b.htm |website=Solomon Encyclopaedia |publisher=Solomon Islands Historical Encyclopaedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>. After being rescued by a [[Royal Navy]] ship in 1875, he returned to Orkney, but at some point he became disillusioned with life in Europe and tried to return to Malaita, but was killed in 1878 at Aoba Island. Upon learning of his death, Kabbou and the people of the village Jack had lived in mourned his death by sacrificing 300 pigs in his name, telling tales of his life for 3 days straight, and building a reliquary house which acted as a shrine to his memory. The shrine survived for 85 years until it burned down in 1963.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Renton, John Jack}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1878 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Orkney]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = John (Jack) Renton\n| image              = \n| birth_date         = Unknown, presumably around 1840\n| birth_place        = [[Orkney]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| death_date         = 1878\n| death_place        = [[Aoba Island]], [[Vanuatu]]\n| occupation         = Seaman, slave, [[headhunting|headhunter]]\n}}\n'''John (Jack) Renton''', also known as \"The White Headhunter\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Randell |first1=Nigel |title=The White Headhunter: The Story of a 19th-Century Sailor Who Survived a South Seas Heart of Darkness |date=July 17, 2003 |publisher=Carroll & Graf |isbn=0786712562}}</ref>, was a Scottish seaman from [[Orkney]] who was shipwrecked in 1868 and landed at Maana'oba Island in the [[Solomon Islands]]. He became a slave of a bigman named Kabbou for 8 years, in which he learnt the Lau language, participated in the island's culture, and became a [[headhunting|headhunter]]. He is the only European to have been a headhunter and was the first European to live for a long period on [[Malaita]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Biographical entry: Renton, John |url=http://www.solomonencyclopaedia.net/biogs/E000656b.htm |website=Solomon Encyclopaedia |publisher=Solomon Islands Historical Encyclopaedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>. After being rescued by a [[Royal Navy]] ship in 1875, he returned to Orkney, but at some point he became disillusioned with life in Europe and tried to return to Malaita, but was killed in 1878 at Aoba Island. Upon learning of his death, Kabbou and the people of the village Jack had lived in mourned his death by sacrificing 300 pigs in his name, telling tales of his life for 3 days straight, and building a reliquary house which acted as a shrine to his memory. The shrine survived for 85 years until it burned down in 1963.\n\n==References==\n\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1878 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Orkney]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "DEFAULTSORT", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Renton"}
